headline: Judge rules in Gov. Scott's favor, orders ballot inspections
subHeadline: Accusations of fraud as Florida Senate race between Rick Scott and Bill Nelson appears headed to a recount; reaction and analysis on 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone, I'm Dana Perino along with Dan Bongino, Marie Harf, Jesse Watters, and Greg Gutfeld. It's 5 o'clock in New York City, and this is "The Five." Florida, once again the epicenter of a major postelection battle, allegations of fraud now being thrown around as two key races move closer toward recounts. Vote counting issues in Broward and Palm Beach County causing senate candidate Rick Scott to file lawsuits accusing officials there of trying to steal the election.

utterances.speaker: RICK SCOTT, REPUBLICAN SENATE CANDIDATE
utterances.sentences: There may be rampant fraud happening in Palm Beach and Broward Counties. And the Broward supervisor of elections, Brenda Snipes, has a history of acting in absolute bad faith for the law which requires that vote by mail and absentee ballots are counted within 30 minutes of polls closing. I will not sit idly by while unethical liberals try to steal this election. Senator Nelson hired one of Hillary Clinton's lawyers from D.C. and the first thing he did was tell reporters he's here to win the election.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: President Trump also weighing in, calling out Broward County's history of election problems.

utterances.speaker: PRESIDENT DONALD TRUMP
utterances.sentences: If you look at Broward County, they have had a horrible history. And if you look at the person, in this case a woman involved, she has had a horrible history. And all of a sudden they're finding votes out of nowhere. And Rick Scott, who won by, you know, it was close, but he won by a comfortable margin, every couple of hours it goes down a little bit. They've hired lawyers and the votes don't ever seem to go the Republican way. It is interesting. It always seems to go the way of the Democrats.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Broward County election supervisor Brenda Snipes taking the brunt of the criticism. Just yesterday, she couldn't give an answer on how many ballots are left to be counted.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Could you just update where things are on the count right now? Just in general.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Could I, please, get a moment to go into room and find out? OK.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And this just breaking, a judge sided with Rick Scott's campaign and is ordering Brenda Snipes to allow immediate inspection of voter records before 7 PM Eastern tonight. So this feels like Deja Vu all over again. And you just saw something on the twitters?

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Yes, Dana. As you know, I love to break news.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: And I have breaking news right here on my phone. I'm going to get to it right now. I'm going to start reading this from my phone, OK? Here we go with some breaking news. This is a tweet from Marco Rubio. You might remember him from running for president. And I believe he's a senator?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Of Florida, yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, thank you.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Little Marco.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: New and troubling allegation has emerged. A statement under penalty perjury that Palm Beach County filled out new ballots to replace damaged ones without allowing campaign representatives to witness the process of creating the new ballot which is required by Florida. So, basically, here you have -- this is my interpretation, not Marco's, that here you have Democrats who've been screaming and yelling about Russian collusion and interfering with elections, and all the time the call has been coming from inside the house. It's the Democrats who are colluding and interfering with elections. How convenient that they find these votes after they lose.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: This is interesting. It took us a long time to finally call that race on election night, Marie. You were sitting there with us. And, actually, Rick Scott, the governor, gave a victory speech before Fox News had actually called the election. It was close but then he did. And right after his victory speech is when Fox News decision desk made the call, but Nelson never conceded and then he hired Mark Elias who is of election fame, right? He was Al Franken's lawyer when Norm Coleman lost in 2008.

utterances.speaker: MARIE HARF, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Yes, and endless. Every vote needs to be counted. We're not even into a recount yet.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: She's got the talking points now.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: So, look, it needs to be done transparently. A judge has ruled now that they need to be more transparent in Broward County, and I think that that's a good thing. This is only the initial count. We're not even in the question of a recount and they're close enough, definitely, one of the races is close enough, the senate race. The governor's race could end up close enough as well. But there is, as of this point, 504 in the east coast on Friday, there is no evidence that we have seen a voter fraud. There's a lot of allegations. There's a lot of people who have partisan interest in these races making claims. And we just need to take a deep breath. We need to have some transparency. We need to get the votes counted. And we also, though, going forward need to make our election systems better in terms of how we do this. Arizona --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Do you like voter I.D.? That'd be great.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: -- still counting votes. California is still counting votes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Because there're a lot of mail in over there.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Eighteen years after the 2000 recount fiasco, the fact that Florida has not fixed their system is actually pretty crazy to me.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Jesse, what do you think of all these?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, he started out Tuesday night, he's got a 60,000 vote margin so he thinks he's got it because the Bush recount, Bush at the end of that night only had a 2,000 vote margin, so very comfortable. And then a day goes by and all these votes come in from Broward. That's kind of fishy. And he sleeps on it and he wakes up and the next thing more votes coming in from Broward. The votes coming in from Broward, 3 to 1 Democrats, and that's a 2 to 1 Democrat, at best, kind of county, all right. And now, they squeeze it down to 15,000 vote margin triggering a recount. Very interesting. Now listen, this woman, we're talking about right now, Snipes, we call her sneaky Snipes already.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Do we?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Do we?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's what we call her. And I used the word --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: That is not what we call her.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Because she's got a history of that. She's been already accused of ballot stuffing, of hiding amendments from ballots. A judge has ruled that she illegally destroyed ballots.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Not in this case.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Not in this case, but --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Is there any evidence in this case?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- in 2016, and in 2018, she was accused of not allowing Scott's representatives to watch her fill up provisional ballots. And the judge has smacked her down and said it's time to open up the doors because you're doing everything in secret. Her number one job is to know how many ballots were cast, how many were counted, and how many are left to be counted. She says she has no idea. And the fact that she's not communicating to the public or to the campaigns how many votes cast, counted, and to be counted is suspicious because if you don't know the tabulation, then anything can happen underneath. And that's why this woman, no one has faith in her at all because especially the way she's conducted herself this day and two years ago.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: There's no evidence.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Go ahead, Dan.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Sneaky Snipes.

utterances.speaker: DAN BONGINO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Have you ever seen that thing on the internet, you have one job?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: You had one job. You're in charge of election, you don't know how many votes are? If there was, ever, minable material that you had one job, Sneaky Snipes. Just count the vote. You can't even count the votes? Now, a couple of things, number one, there may not be direct evidence of fraud, but evidence of irregularities is everywhere. They had to have the votes posted 30 minutes after the polls closed. They didn't. That's just a matter of fact. And another thing, yes, I agree with you, every vote should be counted. Absolutely. That should go across the aisle. The question is when? What's Florida doing, late voting now? So now we're doing early voting? And we're doing postelection ballots?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The Democrats are outperforming Republicans in the late vote.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Marie, point stipulated. The problem is, as Greg accurately stated, she doesn't even know how many votes are to be counted. You have one job.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: But she hasn't even communicated to the campaigns or to the public what the vote count is. That's required by law.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Well, the judge ruled against her, you're right. And by 7 PM tonight, they've said she have to put those numbers out. I think she should be more transparent. I just don't think we should jump to the conclusion that because the races tightening which often happens when provisional ballots get counted that they're somehow fraud. We have to wait for evidence.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Just because the one overseeing it has a history of fraud.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: So should Brian Kampe overseeing Georgia?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: I'm not sure evidence means that what you think it means. Like there is significant evidence of irregularities going on here. She is not -- how do you not have the vote count?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Point out voter fraud evidence to me.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: She didn't even report -- she's not letting people in to actually watch --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: We don't know that.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: No, they're not.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Because they want --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Why follow the lawsuit if you're already watching? They've filled the lawsuit because they've been barred.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: They want -- look, a lot of these lawsuits that we're going to see during this recount are going to be shaky illegal ground but fend for partisan political reason. That happens in every recount. We've seen that. We just have to let the evidence take us where it is.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It is kind of amazing -- and that's not good. Greg, will go back to you. That, either way --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- half of the population there in Florida will think that the other half did something to steal this election from them. That's not good.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The Dems just want to make America suffer. It's like losing the World Series and demanding an extra inning a day later. I have a new nickname, by the way, for Bill Nelson.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: What's that?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Recount Dracula.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Anyway. But we predicted this, I think, last week. We said that no matter what the outcome was, whether the Dems are going to win or lose they won't going to be happy because they're just -- this is too much of their life.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: I'm happy.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: But you're different, Marie. You're a very pleasant person --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Can I say one thing, though, I lost an election by one point. And I won on election day and lost on an absentee count. I conceded. And you can go to The Daily Caller article, I wrote a very nice letter to John Delaney who is now running for president and said -- even people encouraging me to file lawsuit. It's time to move on. This is B.S. --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: But you let the absentee votes get counted. You have them get counted.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: According to the rules. Why do they just --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Why do they just lose in court? Why did she not post 30 minutes after like she's supposed too?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: She's going to have to tonight.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The lesson is never concede.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Jesse made a good point and then we laughed about it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What was --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Don't concede. And Bill Nelson never conceded, but Andrew Gillum did. And now, that one also could end up at a recount.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: That's true.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Recount Dracula.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Pretty good one.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Thanks.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Top Democrats now contradicting themselves over Jeff Sessions' resignation, the must-see tape next.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Greg, stop making me laugh. I'm new at this. Stop. Democratic lawmakers are losing it over Jeff Sessions' resignation. They're now demanding that the Trump administration preserve records relating to Sessions' stepping down. Democrats are also accusing the president of interfering with Bob Mueller's never ending investigation by appointing Mathew Whitaker as acting A.G. The liberal hypocrisy over Sessions is hitting epic levels. Check out this tweet from Senator Elizabeth Warren back in 2017 where she said Sessions needed to resign. But now that he's gone, she's calling it a, quote, constitutional crisis. And Rep. Jerry Nadler also, now, completely flipping his stance, back in 2017, he also said Sessions, quote, must resign as A.G. But now he's saying this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: This is part of the pattern of evidence of interference by the president in the Mueller investigation --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Does that mean obstruction? What does pattern --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Yes. I think that's evidence -- that's certainly evidence of obstruction of justice.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: And last year, house minority leader Nancy Pelosi said anything less than Sessions' resigning is unacceptable. But now she's accusing Trump with trying to interfere with Mueller's investigation. Marie --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: -- this is going to be clashed of the titans on this one. So, I don't get it. We were told by Democrats, including Al Franken when he was in the senate, that Jeff Sessions was part of this massive Russian collusion scheme, he had these unauthorized meetings, that they were totally inappropriate. They attacked and then they demanded he recuse himself. Now he recuses himself and all of a sudden the Democrats are jumping on the Sessions' bandwagon. I guess my question is --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: -- is Sessions part of the scheme or is he the good guy in the outside of the scheme trying to investigate this scheme? I mean, what is it?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Well, I think the Sessions thing is interesting because a lot of those tweets you read were before he recused himself when more information started coming out about his contacts with the Russians. I never said he should resign, but I say he should recuse himself and he did that. You cannot like Jeff Sessions and now think he was a good attorney general. And also believe that you should be worried that President Trump fired him, put someone in that position who has very negative feelings about the Mueller investigation. He has made those clear publicly. And I think preserving records is a definite. We need transparency. And I also think you're going to hear from congress. You know, Jeff Flake and Chris Coons are going to introduce a bill to protect Mueller. It probably won't go anywhere. But I do think when they put a new A.G. up to be confirmed by the senate, you will hear Republicans Susan Collins, Mitt Romney, when he's in the senate, making sure that the new attorney general supports Mueller continuing to the end. That's all we're asking for is Mueller be able to finish his job without interference.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That's all you're saying? Count every vote --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: There're people on the streets protesting the firing of Jeff Sessions. Left-wingers are protesting the firing of a hardcore right-wing. I mean, this guy would give you a lethal injection if you had a man bun. And there are people -- on your side, so many people have free time. To your point yesterday, they're not protesting war or poverty --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: They're protesting obstruction of justice and possible tampering with an ongoing investigation. That's not nothing.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It's not nothing.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: This bothers me. It drives me crazy because none of these concerns seems to present themselves under the Obama administration. And people can say, oh, is what-about-isms. Yes, it is, because what-about-ism means are there principles -- what about -- or are they not?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Finally, someone to defend what-about-ism.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I agree.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: That was a bold move, Bongino.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: I know. Thank you. I mean, Lindsey Graham said it best. Lindsey Graham said, listen, I'm a principle guy. I didn't like Eric Holder. I didn't like -- but I voted for him because he believes the president is entitled to appoint his people. How can the president be charged with obstruction of justice for dismissing -- or asking him to resign? I don't get it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, he has the absolute authority to fire Jeff Sessions. And you always serve at the pleasure of the president, like the letter was written -- it wasn't even dated, it was like, there you go. He probably had it ready for a while. We all knew that he wanted to get rid of Sessions. The president could have a person in there. The thing -- I think the way that he's gone about suggesting Mark Whitaker as the acting A.G. will probably fall apart. And the president today before he left for Paris when he was on the south lawn answering questions, he's like, I don't even know this guy, Mark Whitaker, anyway. So that's usually the sign --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- that's not going to happen. But doesn't really matter that there will be a new attorney general. I do think it's interesting on the protest front, go back to Sessions' hearing. Usually, other senators are quite congenial to the other senators when they're going to be confirmed. Wasn't it Senator Booker that testified against Sessions?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Right. And you add that to --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Brutal to him.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: They were against him, now they're for him. They're like the big Jeff Sessions' fans. It's a little hard to swallow.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Jesse, I still don't get the initial question I post to Marie. And I heard you answered it, but I'm still confused. If Jeff Sessions --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Jesse will clear it up for you.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: I know. I'm going right to him. If Jeff Sessions was part of this intricate conspiracy and had these inappropriate meetings with Russians that caused him to recuse himself, why would you as a Democrat senator, in any way, object to him resigning? Supposedly your case is that he's part of the whole conspiracy. I don't get it. Like, I'm confuse --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't get it, either. I think that, as Greg mentioned yesterday, pot stocks are skyrocketing. Democrats should love that. Now that he's out of there, everyone can smoke weed again, and they should love that. The Democrats love that. Also, can we pull Nadler's face back up on the screen? His eyebrow was as crooked as Hillary. Did you see that thing shoot out to the right like that? I've never seen an eyebrow like that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: My eyebrows get like that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'm an eyebrow connoisseur --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: My eyebrows does that and I come in here and they have to like -- they spend hours combing it --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, with that little pick.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, that little pick.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I know. I have one, too. I would say this --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- Democrats think they can pick Trump's cabinet. In order to pick a cabinet you actually have to win an election --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Or you be in the senate and you advise and consent under the constitution.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Listen, he can pick whoever he wants. I think Whitaker is a great pick, even though Trump never heard of him.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: I just want to thank Mollie Hemingway too for interviewing Jerry Nadler on the Amtrak. Although, Jerry Nadler didn't seem to know (INAUDIBLE). President Trump once again blasting CNN's Jim Acosta and is now threatening to pull more press passes. We'll see you next on The Five.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: President Trump doubling down today on his decision to suspend the press pass of CNN's Jim Acosta after their fiery exchange during the president's news conference on Wednesday.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: I think Jim Acosta is a very unprofessional man. He does this with everybody. He gets paid to do that. I don't think he's a smart person but he's got a loud voice. As far as I'm concerned, I haven't made that decision. But it could be others also. When you're in the White House, this is a very sacred place to me. This is a very special place. You have to treat the White House with respect. You have to treat the presidency with respect.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Trump also took a shot at another White House reporter, April Ryan, calling her a, quote, loser. Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Why do you go to me first?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Because --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: I know this is the president's cheek. I know he does this and he thinks it works with his base, and it probably does. But this week, it went to another level, pulling someone's past, and the words he used today to describe these reporters? I just -- I know I don't like a lot of what Trump does but this really gets to me.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: OK. So, couple of things, for me, there is not a lot of love lost for Jim Acosta amongst the White House press corp., OK? Like, they don't want to say it publicly --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: But you will.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I'm going to tell him. They're trying to do their job and he's making it more difficult because he's a total distraction. And news gathering is what you're supposed do at the White House. There's a mission, right? You're supposed to chronicle the presidency. You can ask the president questions. You hold him to account on behalf of the readers of the newspaper that you work for. So that's the mission of the White House press corps. That's what you're supposed to do. Argumentation is not newsgathering, OK? So they're for one, I think that CNN could make a decision. Is it good for them? Like, who's winning here? Do they think that this is a good thing for them? May be? I do think that we also have to make a distinction that the president and the White House -- they took away the hard pass. That is not a press credential, OK? You can't take away someone's press credentials. The government cannot do that to you. Obama could not do that to Ed Henry when he joined Fox News. Like, that is not possible.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: But you can take away the hard pass.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah. That means you're a security risk. Now, we did revoke somebody's hard pass once because this woman was rifling through colleagues pockets, stealing things, and she was found rifling through --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Who is it?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I'm not going to say.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Come on. Initials, give me the initials.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Was it sneaky Snipes?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What is it rhyme with? Does it rhyme with --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: You wouldn't even know her. So we have to revoke her hard pass. I mean, you can't get back into the White House. You can still get a day pass if the White House approves it. The way I dealt with reporters -- when you couldn't deal with them anymore is I put them in a deep-freeze. There's one reporter, he's probably watching now because he works with an old friend of ours, he's still in the deep-freeze --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Who's that? Who's that? Initials?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: B.F.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: B.F.?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes. And I've told everybody in my office I said no one talks to him. He's in the deep-freeze --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Bob, Barry, Bill, Bob --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Keep trying --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Brian --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Fallon?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: -- Fallon.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Close.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Anyway. I think there's a way that you can deal with it where you put them in the deep-freeze

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: But it's bigger than Acosta. And it's like comments against April Ryan, same reporter's questions were stupid for the president. But, Greg, I saw you laughing when the president said the White House is very sacred.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Here's the deal --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Because he's like -- not exactly a respectful person.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: We know what Trump is. Trump is -- he's a caustic guy. But he's also -- and I said this before, pretty much of a pacifist. So, if you have to look -- would you rather have a super polite dude who just drops bombs or would you rather have a guy who's got a pretty caustic personality but kind of wants to keep America's troops out of harm's way? And I also have to disagree, this is not an attack on the free press. Trump went to Acosta -- one of the first guys he went to, right?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Also, that's what I say about the deep-freeze.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Don't call on him.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: That was a bold move, Bongino.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I know. Thank you. I mean, Lindsey Graham said it best. Lindsey Graham said, listen, I'm a principle guy. I didn't like Eric Holder. I didn't like -- but I voted for him because he believes the president is entitled to appoint his people. How can the president be charged with obstruction of justice for dismissing -- or asking him to resign? I don't get it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, he has the absolute authority to fire Jeff Sessions. And you always serve at the pleasure of the president, like the letter was written -- it wasn't even dated, it was like, there you go. He probably had it ready for a while. We all knew that he wanted to get rid of Sessions. The president could have a person in there. The thing -- I think the way that he's gone about suggesting Mark Whitaker as the acting A.G. will probably fall apart. And the president today before he left for Paris when he was on the south lawn answering questions, he's like, I don't even know this guy, Mark Whitaker, anyway. So that's usually the sign --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- that's not going to happen. But doesn't really matter that there will be a new attorney general. I do think it's interesting on the protest front, go back to Sessions' hearing. Usually, other senators are quite congenial to the other senators when they're going to be confirmed. Wasn't it Senator Booker that testified against Sessions?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Right. And you add that to --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Brutal to him.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They were against him, now they're for him. They're like the big Jeff Sessions' fans. It's a little hard to swallow.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Jesse, I still don't get the initial question I post to Marie. And I heard you answered it, but I'm still confused. If Jeff Sessions --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Jesse will clear it up for you.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I know. I'm going right to him. If Jeff Sessions was part of this intricate conspiracy and had these inappropriate meetings with Russians that caused him to recuse himself, why would you as a Democrat senator, in any way, object to him resigning? Supposedly your case is that he's part of the whole conspiracy. I don't get it. Like, I'm confuse --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't get it, either. I think that, as Greg mentioned yesterday, pot stocks are skyrocketing. Democrats should love that. Now that he's out of there, everyone can smoke weed again, and they should love that. The Democrats love that. Also, can we pull Nadler's face back up on the screen? His eyebrow was as crooked as Hillary. Did you see that thing shoot out to the right like that? I've never seen an eyebrow like that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: My eyebrows get like that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm an eyebrow connoisseur --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: My eyebrows does that and I come in here and they have to like -- they spend hours combing it --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, with that little pick.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, that little pick.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I know. I have one, too. I would say this --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- Democrats think they can pick Trump's cabinet. In order to pick a cabinet you actually have to win an election --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Or you be in the senate and you advise and consent under the constitution.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Listen, he can pick whoever he wants. I think Whitaker is a great pick, even though Trump never heard of him.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I just want to thank Mollie Hemingway too for interviewing Jerry Nadler on the Amtrak. Although, Jerry Nadler didn't seem to know (INAUDIBLE). President Trump once again blasting CNN's Jim Acosta and is now threatening to pull more press passes. We'll see you next on The Five.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: President Trump doubling down today on his decision to suspend the press pass of CNN's Jim Acosta after their fiery exchange during the president's news conference on Wednesday.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: I think Jim Acosta is a very unprofessional man. He does this with everybody. He gets paid to do that. I don't think he's a smart person but he's got a loud voice. As far as I'm concerned, I haven't made that decision. But it could be others also. When you're in the White House, this is a very sacred place to me. This is a very special place. You have to treat the White House with respect. You have to treat the presidency with respect.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Trump also took a shot at another White House reporter, April Ryan, calling her a, quote, loser. Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Why do you go to me first?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Because --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: I know this is the president's cheek. I know he does this and he thinks it works with his base, and it probably does. But this week, it went to another level, pulling someone's past, and the words he used today to describe these reporters? I just -- I know I don't like a lot of what Trump does but this really gets to me.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: OK. So, couple of things, for me, there is not a lot of love lost for Jim Acosta amongst the White House press corp., OK? Like, they don't want to say it publicly --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But you will.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm going to tell him. They're trying to do their job and he's making it more difficult because he's a total distraction. And news gathering is what you're supposed do at the White House. There's a mission, right? You're supposed to chronicle the presidency. You can ask the president questions. You hold him to account on behalf of the readers of the newspaper that you work for. So that's the mission of the White House press corps. That's what you're supposed to do. Argumentation is not newsgathering, OK? So they're for one, I think that CNN could make a decision. Is it good for them? Like, who's winning here? Do they think that this is a good thing for them? May be? I do think that we also have to make a distinction that the president and the White House -- they took away the hard pass. That is not a press credential, OK? You can't take away someone's press credentials. The government cannot do that to you. Obama could not do that to Ed Henry when he joined Fox News. Like, that is not possible.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: But you can take away the hard pass.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah. That means you're a security risk. Now, we did revoke somebody's hard pass once because this woman was rifling through colleagues pockets, stealing things, and she was found rifling through --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Who is it?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm not going to say.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Come on. Initials, give me the initials.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Was it sneaky Snipes?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What is it rhyme with? Does it rhyme with --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You wouldn't even know her. So we have to revoke her hard pass. I mean, you can't get back into the White House. You can still get a day pass if the White House approves it. The way I dealt with reporters -- when you couldn't deal with them anymore is I put them in a deep-freeze. There's one reporter, he's probably watching now because he works with an old friend of ours, he's still in the deep-freeze --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Who's that? Who's that? Initials?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: B.F.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: B.F.?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes. And I've told everybody in my office I said no one talks to him. He's in the deep-freeze --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Bob, Barry, Bill, Bob --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Keep trying --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Brian --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Fallon?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- Fallon.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Close.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Anyway. I think there's a way that you can deal with it where you put them in the deep-freeze

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: But it's bigger than Acosta. And it's like comments against April Ryan, same reporter's questions were stupid for the president. But, Greg, I saw you laughing when the president said the White House is very sacred.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Here's the deal --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Because he's like -- not exactly a respectful person.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We know what Trump is. Trump is -- he's a caustic guy. But he's also -- and I said this before, pretty much of a pacifist. So, if you have to look -- would you rather have a super polite dude who just drops bombs or would you rather have a guy who's got a pretty caustic personality but kind of wants to keep America's troops out of harm's way? And I also have to disagree, this is not an attack on the free press. Trump went to Acosta -- one of the first guys he went to, right?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Also, that's what I say about the deep-freeze.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Don't call on him.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. And he got three questions. He got three questions and then he started poking the bear. And then Trump -- if it was an attack on the press, why did Trump stay for 90 minutes?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Because he loves it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. That's good for everybody.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And that's the other thing --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The White House press corp., one of the reasons they're frustrated is because Jim Acosta is a distraction, the president have been really willing to take questions from the press. Everytime he goes out to Marine One he's been willing -- yes. And so, if Acosta makes it so that it's harder to ask question for the president, it hurts everybody else trying to do their job and fulfill their mission.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Jesse, should the president call reporters losers?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: If they're losers, you know --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: You think April Ryan should probably called that name.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't know much about her, so I can't really comment on it. I do know about Acosta, not personally, but his conduct is totally unbecoming. And, you know, as someone that really prides himself as someone that conducts himself in a very professional way...

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, I've seen your -- I've seen your beach -- I've seen your beach coverage!

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think I can pass judgment. No, in all seriousness, he was looking for a confrontation. He got --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Who? Donald Trump or --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Acosta got what he wanted, then got put in a timeout, and he should just take his medicine. OK, he's not -- he thinks he's, like, the Rosa Parks of the White House press corps. This is not a threat to the First Amendment. You're fine. They revoked your press pass.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think it's important. It's your hard -- the hard pass. See, like, because I think the press, or some on the left, are trying to say, "Oh, he's -- this is a First Amendment issue," that they're taking away the right to do their job. No, they're just saying that you can't come in the building, because it's a security issue.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: You get the last word in.

utterances.speaker: DAN BONGINO, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Serious question, though: has Acosta ever broken a story that's not about Acosta? He writes stories about himself. And I want to thank him, because he managed to direct the conversation away from the Democrats', I think, rather successful night. A split decision, but a good night to stories about, again, Jim Acosta --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Exactly.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: -- who most conservatives generally at this point tend to just dislike because of what he does. So good job, Jim Acosta. I appreciate it. Getting us ready for 2020.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Oh, God. OK. Coming up, one dad pushes the limit on helping his son's youth soccer team. That and more in "The Fastest Seven," up next.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Welcome back. Time for "The Fastest Seven." First up, take a good look at "The Five" right now, because we're all going to be extinct. Greg first. China has created an artificial news anchor. Check this out.

utterances.speaker: ROBOTIC VOICE
utterances.utterance: Hello, everyone. I'm an English Artificial Intelligence Anchor. This is my very first day in Xinhua News Agency. My voice and appearance are --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Sounds like Wolf Blitzer, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It does -- he would fit in at CNN. But you know what? We have nothing to worry about, because A.I. can only replace hard news. But they can't do what we can do. You can't do opinions. You don't want to hear A.I. opinion. You know, if they report it straight, it's just like a news wire. But not this. We're saved. Trust me.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We're good. We're good.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Thank God. I don't have any other skills -- Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, I think that you might soon see him replacing Jim Acosta at the White House.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You can't take his pass.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He has more life than Acosta.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Give up the microphone.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Can you imagine if they did, though, create A.I. versions of all of us? What that would look like.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Maybe we are. Maybe this is a simulation, Marie. We could be created, actually. We might be part of an algorithm.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: And we just don't know?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: You didn't take the blue pill?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Listen, let's be honest --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: This blew my mind.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: A.I., your job is safe. No one else could've thought of "Sneaky Snipes." There is no A.I. that would have thought of that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's -- that's what we call her.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: No chance, brother.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: The nickname producer.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. Up next, are you a pushy parent? Watch as one dad takes it to the extreme at his son's soccer game.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Holy crap.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I kind of liked it. Bongino, what do you think?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Listen, I've got kids. You do anything for your kids. You don't even care about becoming, like, a YouTube infamous person. You just do it. It's like I would totally do the same thing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'd do the same thing. I like it.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Hat tip to that cat.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'd do the same thing.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Good job.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'll allow it. What do you think, Marie?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: I think my dad would totally do it, too. Also, this is in Wales, right, in the U.K.?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They take it quite seriously there.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: They take very -- soccer, football, very seriously.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's true. But you can't get in trouble for that.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: That poor kid. I think the kid probably hates soccer, or football, and he doesn't want to play it anymore. And now his dad just pushed him and made him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think it was a great save. Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: A couple of things. This is one of the reasons I don't have kids, because I don't want to attend kids' sports. I hated attending my own games as a kid. Why would I want to go see other -- kids play sports very poorly. They can't --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: In high school, that's another story. That age, you're right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Also, you know, that made the game interesting. So why not break incorporate that into the game?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Put a dad on the other side.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Put a dad on the other side.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wow, I like that idea. All right. And finally, the PC police on full patrol across the pond. The European Union setting new guidelines on what's appropriate for gender- based words. Here are some examples. Something that's "man-made" is now "artificial."

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, jeez.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: "Headmasters" are now "principals." And instead of "mankind," they're told to say "humanity." This is just so weak. They're just changing the English language to appease weaklings, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, here's the thing. We were -- when we were growing up, we saw, you know, books like "1984," and there was always this idea that government was going to be the people controlling our lives. Actually, it's coming from academia. People graduate from the campus in which they believe in language control and speech codes; and they're moving out now into the real world. And this is the -- and this is the result is you're going to have -- you're having people actually tell you what to say and what not to say. And you can be punished for it. I have some words I wanted to ban.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, good.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Shenanigan, sheep, shepherd, Sherlock, Sherpa, shed, sheriff, sherry, and Shetland. They all contain the word "she."

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Were you just -- didn't you want to ban "leaving it all on the field," too?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, I did. I banned that a couple -- I do ban a lot of things.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: See, I do watch the show, too.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That little goalie left it all out on the field.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Literally.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What do you think? If I said "mankind," would that ring a bell? Would that trigger something in your mind?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You wouldn't even think, right?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: No, I'm not offended by that. I want governments -- or this is the E.U., right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: So it's a governmental body. Like, maybe they should focus on women making as much as men, equal pay, and not what words we use.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We don't have that problem here, Marie?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Do we not have that problem?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No. I don't buy into your myths.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: I'm fact-checking you on that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, Greg, she's making more than you are.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: No, like, there are real things to worry about. The E.U. has real problems. This is not one of them.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's right. Like those tariffs. Those have got to come down on the cars. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: I lived in England for a year when I met Peter and then went over there, and I had to leave. The rules, there are so many rules!

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The rules were holding you back, Dana. You're a free spirit.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Dana, she cannot be contained.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: "All of these rules, man. I've got to get out of England and go to America."

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: "I go to bed at 8 p.m. They tell me 7:30, I will stay up a half an hour later."

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: "I'll have 2 tablespoons, not just one!"

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: "I will read as many books as I want. My book club is open for everybody."

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Bongino.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Did you ever see -- remember that horrible movie, "Demolition Man" with Sylvester Stallone?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: You see that?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, yes, yes.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: You go back and watch that movie now --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's amazing.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: And you want to talk about how quickly the cultures change. It was satirical --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: -- when Sandra Bullock starts telling Sylvester Stallone, "We don't use these terms now." Watch that movie now.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: It's prophetic, not satirical.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I've always said, Sylvester Stallone, ahead of his time. Stay right there. Fan Mail Friday is up next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: "Fan Mail Friday"! We're answering your burning questions. That sounds painful, doesn't it? OK. @Frenchifirecracker begins with a great question. I love this question. "What's the most interesting thing you can see out of your kitchen window?" I think I'm going to give it to you first, Dana, because I have a feeling you have something outside your window.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, first of all, I have to stand on my tiptoes so I can see out of the kitchen window. Yes, I've got something to say. This building across the street from me --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- is redoing its roof, OK? So there's been these guys working there for about six months. I cannot believe I'm going to say this. I watch these guys.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Does Peter know?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They go to the bathroom on the roof!

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Over the roof?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, they can't --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No, not over the roof.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: On the roof?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Down the drain on the roof!

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's not -- that's --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That is disgusting.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That is disgusting.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes. I can see that out my window.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You should film it and give it to, like, an intrepid reporter on the local news.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't know. Maybe they're not allowed to go anywhere else to use the restroom, but it's like, kind of like, you guys, you're surrounded by buildings. What are you thinking?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Oh, my God.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Terrible, Marie. I would never pee in the open doors, open places. Anymore.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Today.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, today.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: So I live in an apartment building in D.C., and across -- right across from us is a guy who I think is growing weed in his apartment, but he keeps his television on 24/7, all day every day --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: on FOX News?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: No, I don't think so. He, like --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think he's a CNN guy.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: He walks around in various states of dress, often holding a cat.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Nice.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: And so there's this, like, character, who -- and you can see him right out of our window, and he has these bizarre lights that I think help with the pot.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Those are called heat lamps. My friend told me.
